column3: Fixed-Size parts will not stretch based on how they're used.
Brackets connect elements at an angle.
Closers force elements to close.
Dog doors let dogs and other animals in and out.
Doorbells allow visitors to announce their arrival.
FF&E stands for "Fixtures, Furniture and Equipment".
Decorations help the building feel hospitable and beautiful.
Electrical fixtures use electricity to provide a service to occupants.
Lights illuminate the space.
Chandeliers hang ornately from the ceiling.
Floor lamps stand on the floor.
Floor sconces are embedded in the floor.
Pendants hang from the ceiling.
Recessed cans are embedded in the ceiling.
Table lamps stand on tables.
Track lights include multiple light fixtures attached and powered by a track.
Wall sconces are embedded in the wall.
Entourage are the characters in a scene.
Furniture are the objects that allow people to use a space for a purpose.
Beds are where people sleep.
Chairs are where people sit.
Accent chairs are usually eye-catching and used solo.
Bench chairs are linear and seat multiple people.
Dining chairs are used around tables for eating.
Lounge chairs are used to recline and relax.
Stools usually have little-to-no back.
Task chairs are for working.
Dressers usually store clothes in drawers.
Sofas are where people sit in groups.
Tables are surfaces on which people put things - work, meals, decorations, etc.
Coffee tables are low tables that are used alongside seating areas.
Desks are where people do work.
Dining tables are where people eat.
Side tables are small tables used in corners alongside seating.
Furniture sets are groups of different furniture meant to be used together.
Knobs allow you to twist, disengage, then pull a panel forward.
Lateral pulls allow you to pull a panel to the side.
Pulls allow you to pull a panel forward.
Planar modules are boards, bricks, sheets, planks, tiles, shingles, etc that always lie flat in their construction layer.

column3: Volumetric modules are bricks and blocks that are often turned multiple directions in their masonry bond patterns.
Rollers allow elements to roll.
Linear parts stretch in 1 dimension (e.g. studs, joists, track lights, pull bars, beams, etc).

column3: Planar parts stretch in 2 dimensions (e.g. frames, operable panels, screens, shutters).
Flexible-Size parts are amorphous and stretch based on their use (e.g. air, water, concrete, gravel).
"Assemblies" are made of arrays of lesser Parts.

column2: Fixed Size (all 3 dimensions set by Preset)
column3: Fixed-Size assemblies will not stretch based on how they're used.
Slot-Based assemblies have a fixed number of pre-designed slots.
Handle Sets include interior and exterior handles in one hardware set.
Linear assemblies stretch in 1 dimension (e.g. dentil trim, compound balusters).
Pattern-based assemblies create as many slot repetitions as they can along their stretch dimensions.
Group-based assemblies create a pre-designed number of slots perpendicular to their stretch dimensions.
Slot-Based assemblies have a fixed number of pre-designed slots.
Compound Muntins have front and back surface-mounted muntins (and often a spacer between glass panes).
Planar assemblies stretch in 2 dimensions (e.g. layers, layered assemblies, doors).
Layers are arrays of modules that repeat in 2 dimensions.
Layer groups are multi-layered assemblies (e.g. walls, floors, roofs).
Slot-Based assemblies have a fixed number of pre-designed slots (e.g. doors, windows, panels).
Muntin sets are the sum of all muntins on a pane of glass.
Panel assemblies are the sum of a panel plus its attachments.
Panel Sets are multiple sectional panel assemblies acting as one Panel (e.g. garage doors).
Cabinet Faces are a collection of panel assemblies and a frame (and, often, hinges). It goes on the front of a cabinet carcass.
Doors are a collection of panel assemblies and a frame (and, often, hinges).
Windows are a collection of panel assemblies and a frame (and, often, hinges).
Serrated assemblies stack their parts in a zigzag pattern.
Monolithic stairs use one part for their treads, risers, and spanning support (no stringers).
Stringer stairs use linear parts ("stringers") to hold their treads and risers.
Flexible-Size assemblies do not have a predetermined size, and will stretch in all 3 dimensions based on their use.
Prismic assemblies take a shape and extrude it (e.g. Cabinets).
Cabinets are a wooden box ("carcass") with a means of putting things inside it ("cabinet face").
Slot-Based assemblies have a fixed number of pre-designed slots (e.g. rig track sets).
Track Sets are multiple tracks (e.g. for overhead doors) assembled into a set.
